Subject: journald: set a limit on the number of fields (1k)
Origin: https://github.com/systemd/systemd/commit/052c57f132f04a3cf4148f87561618da1a6908b4
Bug-RedHat: https://bugzilla.redhat.com/show_bug.cgi?id=1653861
Bug-Debian: https://bugs.debian.org/918848
Bug-Debian-Security: https://security-tracker.debian.org/tracker/CVE-2018-16865

We allocate a iovec entry for each field, so with many short entries,
our memory usage and processing time can be large, even with a relatively
small message size. Let's refuse overly long entries.

CVE-2018-16865

What from I can see, the problem is not from an alloca, despite what the CVE
description says, but from the attack multiplication that comes from creating
many very small iovecs: (void* + size_t) for each three bytes of input
message.
---
 src/journal/journal-file.h    | 3 +++
 src/journal/journald-native.c | 4 ++++
 2 files changed, 7 insertions(+)

diff --git a/src/journal/journal-file.h b/src/journal/journal-file.h
index dd8ef52d2..37749c445 100644
--- a/src/journal/journal-file.h
+++ b/src/journal/journal-file.h
@@ -158,6 +158,9 @@ int journal_file_open_reliably(
  * files without adding too many zeros. */
 #define OFSfmt "%06"PRIx64
 
+/* The maximum number of fields in an entry */
+#define ENTRY_FIELD_COUNT_MAX 1024
+
 static inline bool VALID_REALTIME(uint64_t u) {
         /* This considers timestamps until the year 3112 valid. That should be plenty room... */
         return u > 0 && u < (1ULL << 55);
diff --git a/src/journal/journald-native.c b/src/journal/journald-native.c
index cf3349393..0c451274f 100644
--- a/src/journal/journald-native.c
+++ b/src/journal/journald-native.c
@@ -134,6 +134,10 @@ void server_process_native_message(
                 }
 
                 /* A property follows */
